The dynamic mean-field model (MFM) was used to simulate neural dynamics of the 68 cortical ROIs34. Based on the simulated neural activity at each ROI, the hemodynamic model35,36 was then used to simulate blood oxygen level-dependent (BOLD) fMRI. Details of the model can be found in the Methods section. Here we highlight the intuitions behind the MFM. In the MFM, the neural dynamics of each ROI are driven by four components: (1) recurrent (intra-regional) input, (2) inter-regional inputs, (3) external input (potentially from subcortical relays), and (4) neuronal noise. There are “free” parameters associated with each component. First, a larger recurrent connection strength \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$w$$\end{document}w corresponds to a stronger recurrent input current. Second, the inter-regional inputs depend on the neural activities of other cortical ROIs and the connectional strength between ROIs. The inter-regional connectional strength is parameterized by the SC matrices, scaled by a global scaling constant \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$G$$\end{document}G. Third, \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$I$$\end{document}I is the external input current. Fourth, the neuronal noise is assumed to be Gaussian with a standard deviation \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
